questions.scenario:
You are debugging a production issue where a transactional payment processing system fails to roll back a nested database transaction when an external service call fails. The developer designed `validateAndExecute` to run in a new isolated transaction so that failure audit logs can be written regardless of the main transaction's outcome. However, during an outage, the outer transaction committed partial state, and the nested transaction was never created.

java
@Service
public class PaymentService {
    @Transactional
    public void processPayment(PaymentRequest request) {
        try {
            validateAndExecute(request);
        } catch (PaymentException e) {
            // Logic to log locally
        }
    }

    @Transactional(propagation = Propagation.REQUIRES_NEW)
    public void validateAndExecute(PaymentRequest request) throws PaymentException {
        if (externalServiceCallFails()) {
            throw new PaymentException("External API Down");
        }
        // Database writes...
    }
}

You are debugging a production issue where a distributed worker queue fails to process dead-letter-queue (DLQ) messages because a custom rollback-on-exception mechanism catches `Throwable` instead of `Exception`. When an `OutOfMemoryError` occurs, the application incorrectly attempts to send a rollback message over the network inside the `catch (Throwable t)` block.

java
public void processMessage(Message msg) {
    try {
        executeBusinessLogic(msg);
    } catch (Throwable t) {
        broker.sendToDLQ(msg, t.getMessage());
        rollbackTransaction();
    }
}
